Accidents Data Set¶

In my recent project, I worked with a comprehensive UK road accident dataset comprising over 300,000 records collected between 2021 and 2022. The scale and richness of this dataset make it highly valuable for data-driven decision-making in road safety and urban planning. To extract actionable insights, I used python to apply the K-Means clustering algorithm, a widely used unsupervised machine learning technique, to categorize the accidents into two key dimensions:

1. Clustering by Accident Severity¶

Accidents were grouped based on their severity, classified into three official categories. I enhanced interpretability by assigning distinct color-coded clusters: 🟣 Slight (85.5%)– Minor accidents with minimal impact 🟠 Serious (13.2%)– Moderate severity requiring medical attention 🟡 Fatal (1.3%)– High-impact or deadly accidents This severity-based clustering allows authorities to identify high-risk areas and allocate resources accordingly.

2. Clustering by Geographic Location.¶

Using latitude and longitude, I segmented accident locations into four spatial clusters aligned with compass directions. These help visualize regional accident patterns across the UK:. 🟡 South East (↘️) – Including areas around London and Kent\n 🔵 South West (↙️) – Covering Cornwall, Devon, and surrounding counties\n 🟠 Central (⏺) – Midlands and surrounding inland regions\n 🟣 North (↑) – Encompassing Northern England and parts of Scotland\n This geographical segmentation highlights regional trends and supports location-specific safety strategies.\n By combining severity-based and location-based clustering, this project provides valuable insight into where and how severely accidents occur—offering guidance for emergency response planning, policy decisions, and road safety improvements.

In [33]:
inertia = []
k_range = range(1, 9)

for k in k_range:
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
    km.fit(X_encoded)
    inertia.append(km.inertia_)

plt.plot(k_range, inertia, marker='o')
plt.title('Elbow Method for Optimal K')
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters (K)')
plt.ylabel('Inertia')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

# 1. Clustering by LOCATION
# --------------------------
geo_df_loc = df[['Latitude', 'Longitude']].dropna()
X_loc = geo_df_loc[['Latitude', 'Longitude']].values

kmeans_loc = KMeans(n_clusters=4, random_state=42)
geo_df_loc['Cluster_Location'] = kmeans_loc.fit_predict(X_loc)

# Create map for Location-based Clusters
fig1 = px.scatter_mapbox(
    geo_df_loc,
    lat='Latitude',
    lon='Longitude',
    color='Cluster_Location',
    zoom=4,
    height=800,
    title='Clusters Based on Accident Location',
    hover_data={'Cluster_Location': True}
)

fig1.update_layout(mapbox_style='open-street-map')
fig1.write_html('location_clusters_map.html')

# --------------------------
# 2. Clustering by SEVERITY
# --------------------------
geo_df_sev = df[['Latitude', 'Longitude', 'Accident_Severity']].dropna()

le = LabelEncoder()
severity_encoded = le.fit_transform(geo_df_sev['Accident_Severity'])
X_sev = severity_encoded.reshape(-1, 1)

kmeans_sev = KMeans(n_clusters=3, random_state=42)
geo_df_sev['Cluster_Severity'] = kmeans_sev.fit_predict(X_sev)

# Create map for Severity-based Clusters
fig2 = px.scatter_mapbox(
    geo_df_sev,
    lat='Latitude',
    lon='Longitude',
    color='Cluster_Severity',
    zoom=4,
    height=800,
    title='Clusters Based on Accident Severity',
    hover_data=['Accident_Severity', 'Cluster_Severity']
)

fig2.update_layout(mapbox_style='open-street-map')
fig2.write_html('severity_clusters_map.html')
